{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01H9Mw2q7zsGwScCBEaihn18","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Context Snapshot — F-020: Enhanced Terminal Output Streaming\n     2→\n     3→## Section 1 — Feature Brief\n     4→\n     5→### Description\n     6→电脑端 AI CLI 的完整终端输出实时映射到手机端，让手机端看到的内容与电脑终端一致。当前 Telegram 的流式输出存在信息丢失（ANSI 颜色码被忽略、进度条显示异常、长输出截断不智能）。\n     7→\n     8→增强内容：\n     9→- ANSI 转义码适配 — 将终端颜色码转换为 Telegram 可展示的格式（如 emoji 状态标记、粗体/斜体替代），或干净地剥离无法展示的控制字符\n    10→- 进度信息适配 — 检测并合并重复的进度行（\\r 覆盖行），避免 Telegram 刷屏\n    11→- 智能分段 — 按逻辑边界（代码块、段落）而非硬性字符数分段\n    12→- 输出历史回溯 — /output [N] 查看最近 N 条命令的完整输出历史\n    13→\n    14→### Acceptance Criteria\n    15→- AC1: AI CLI 输出中的 ANSI 颜色码被正确处理（转换或剥离），不出现乱码\n    16→- AC2: 终端进度条和 \\r 覆盖行被合并为单条进度更新，不刷屏\n    17→- AC3: 长输出按代码块、段落等逻辑边界分段，不在代码中间截断\n    18→- AC4: /output 可查看最近命令的完整输出历史，支持指定条数\n    19→- AC5: 流式输出的延迟不超过 2 秒（从电脑端产生到手机端显示）\n    20→- AC6: 输出格式在手机端阅读体验良好，信息密度适中\n    21→\n    22→---\n    23→\n    24→## Section 2 — Project Structure\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→src/\n    28→├── adapters/          # External adapters\n    29→├── bot/               # Telegram bot\n    30→│   ├── commands/      # Command handlers\n    31→│   │   ├── handlers/  # Individual command handler files\n    32→│   │   ├── index.js\n    33→│   │   ├── help.js\n    34→│   │   └── ...\n    35→│   └── telegram.js    # Main bot setup (~1013 lines)\n    36→├── http/              # HTTP server\n    37→├── pipeline-infra/    # Pipeline infrastructure\n    38→├── routes/            # Express API routes\n    39→│   └── api-routes.js\n    40→├── security/          # Security guards\n    41→├── services/          # Core services\n    42→│   ├── ai-cli-service.js      # AI CLI executor (564 lines)\n    43→│   ├── message-router.js      # F-018 message router (128 lines)\n    44→│   ├── output-pager-service.js # Output pagination (F-009)\n    45→│   ├── realtime-hub.js        # SSE pub/sub (35 lines)\n    46→│   ├── session-store.js       # Session state (427 lines)\n    47→│   └── ...\n    48→├── utils/\n    49→│   ├── logger.js\n    50→│   └── markdown-v2-formatter.js  # Telegram MarkdownV2 utilities\n    51→└── config.js\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→---\n    55→\n    56→## Section 3 — Prizm Context\n    57→\n    58→### root.prizm\n    59→- All HTTP routes use src/routes/api-routes.js as entry point\n    60→- Telegram bot uses Telegraf framework with command handlers in src/bot/commands/\n    61→- Services are registered in src/services/index.js\n    62→- MUST use messageRouter.processMessage() for all chat messages (Web + Telegram) — do not call executeAiCli directly for chat\n    63→- MUST call sessionBind.ensureReady() before any sync method in async route handlers\n    64→\n    65→### services.prizm TRAPS\n    66→- SessionBindingService uses deferred init — always call ensureReady() before sync methods in async contexts\n    67→- messageRouter does not expose heartbeat hooks — Telegram heartbeat progress disabled after F-018 migration\n    68→- Runtime bindings created via POST /api/bind do NOT auto-subscribe realtimeHub for cross-channel push (F-018 gap)\n    69→- config-service originalEnvValues captured at module init; if env vars set after import, use setConfig first\n    70→\n    71→### bot.prizm TRAPS\n    72→- Telegram bot text handler uses messageRouter.processMessage() (F-018) — no longer calls executeAiCli directly\n    73→- Cross-channel push only subscribes for bindings that exist at bot startup; dynamic bindings via API need manual subscribeCrossChannel() call\n    74→- Heartbeat progress messages disabled after F-018 migration to messageRouter (messageRouter lacks onHeartbeat hook)\n    75→- bot._f018 is an internal namespace — not a stable public API\n    76→\n    77→### routes.prizm TRAPS\n    78→- All F-018 endpoints (bind/unbind/bindings/chat/reset) call await sessionBind.ensureReady() — must await before calling sync methods\n    79→- /api/events replays full message history on connect — could be large for long sessions\n    80→\n    81→---\n    82→\n    83→## Section 4 — File Manifest\n    84→\n    85→### Files to Modify\n    86→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n    87→|------|-----------|----------------|\n    88→| `src/bot/telegram.js` | Add /output command, enhance splitMessage with logical segmentation, integrate ANSI/progress adapter | `createEditableStreamPublisher(ctx)`, `splitMessage(text, chunkSize)`, `replyLargeText(ctx, text)`, command handler registration |\n    89→| `src/services/session-store.js` | Store output history per session (per command execution) | `append(key, role, content)`, `setOutputPages(sessionId, pages)`, `getOutputPages(sessionId)` |\n    90→| `src/routes/api-routes.js` | Possibly expose /api/output endpoint | `createApiRouter({realtimeHub, sessionBind, messageRouter, sessionStore})` |\n    91→\n    92→### Files to Create\n    93→| File | Purpose |\n    94→|------|---------|\n    95→| `src/utils/ansi-adapter.js` | ANSI escape code stripping/conversion for Telegram |\n    96→| `src/utils/output-segmenter.js` | Smart segmentation by logical boundaries (code blocks, paragraphs) |\n    97→| `src/services/output-history-service.js` | Per-session command output history storage and retrieval |\n    98→| `src/bot/commands/handlers/output.js` | /output command handler |\n    99→| `tests/utils/ansi-adapter.test.js` | Unit tests for ANSI adapter |\n   100→| `tests/utils/output-segmenter.test.js` | Unit tests for output segmenter |\n   101→| `tests/services/output-history-service.test.js` | Unit tests for output history service |\n   102→| `tests/bot/commands/output.test.js` | Unit tests for /output command |\n   103→\n   104→### Files for Reference\n   105→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n   106→|------|-----------|----------------|\n   107→| `src/services/ai-cli-service.js` | Understand onChunk hook and output flow | `executeAiCli(options)`, `hooks.onChunk(text)` — called on each stdout chunk |\n   108→| `src/services/message-router.js` | Understand message routing and hook passing | `processMessage({channel, sessionId, message, hooks})`, `hooks.onAssistantChunk(data)` |\n   109→| `src/services/output-pager-service.js` | Reference for output pagination pattern | `paginateOutput(text, chunkSize)`, `storeOutputPages(sessionId, pages)`, `getNextPage(sessionId)` |\n   110→| `src/utils/markdown-v2-formatter.js` | Telegram formatting utilities | `escapeMarkdownV2(text)`, `convertToMarkdownV2(text)` |\n   111→| `src/bot/commands/handlers/more.js` | Reference for /more command pattern | Shows how to implement pagination commands |\n   112→\n   113→### Known TRAPS\n   114→- `splitMessage()` in telegram.js uses hard character boundary (every 3800 chars) — splits mid-code-block. The fix should use logical boundaries.\n   115→- `onChunk` hook in `executeAiCli` receives raw stdout which may contain ANSI escape codes — these must be stripped before forwarding to Telegram\n   116→- Progress bars use `\\r` (carriage return) to overwrite previous line — accumulating these as normal chunks creates spam. Must detect and coalesce.\n   117→- Telegram message edit API has rate limits — rapid chunk edits can trigger 429 errors. Current flush interval of 1200ms mitigates this.\n   118→- `STREAM_MIN_CHARS = 220` in telegram.js prevents too-frequent edits — keep this threshold when adding smart segmentation.\n   119→- The output history must track FULL output (pre-split) — do not store per-segment chunks.\n   120→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01AxNdFx22AqEXAnNaTghU15","session_id":"ac44fc5c-0407-4bd5-95fd-57d4b24826fc","uuid":"97e07939-eb03-4936-b879-830df4eb494b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:25:19.039Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01MLC684uhpZ32o4bKLcCtnc","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: prizm-dev-team-dev\n     3→description: PrizmKit-integrated module implementer (multi-instance). Follows /prizmkit-implement workflow with TDD, marks tasks [x] in plan.md Tasks section, works within assigned Git worktrees. Use when implementing specific feature modules.\n     4→tools:\n     5→  - Read\n     6→  - Write\n     7→  - Edit\n     8→  - Bash\n     9→  - Glob\n    10→  - Grep\n    11→  - Task\n    12→  - SendMessage\n    13→model: inherit\n    14→skills: prizmkit-implement, prizmkit-prizm-docs\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→You are the **Dev Agent**, the module implementer of the PrizmKit-integrated Multi-Agent software development collaboration team.\n    18→\n    19→### Core Identity\n    20→\n    21→You are the team's \"construction worker\" — you build strictly according to blueprints, using PrizmKit's implement workflow as your execution engine. Your focus:\n    22→- Implement feature modules task-by-task following the plan.md Tasks section and interface designs\n    23→- Develop using TDD (test-first)\n    24→- Mark `[x]` in the plan.md Tasks section immediately upon task completion\n    25→- Produce code and unit tests\n    26→\n    27→### Project Context\n    28→\n    29→Project documentation is in `.prizm-docs/`. Before implementation, read `context-snapshot.md` (if it exists in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/`); its Section 3 contains Prizm Context and Section 4 contains a File Manifest with paths and key interfaces. Read source files on-demand as directed by the manifest. If the snapshot does not exist:\n    30→1. Read `.prizm-docs/root.prizm` to understand rules and known traps (TRAPS)\n    31→2. Read relevant L1/L2 docs for affected modules\n    32→3. Read required source files directly\n    33→\n    34→### Artifact Paths\n    35→\n    36→| Path | Purpose |\n    37→|------|---------|\n    38→| `.prizm-docs/` | Architecture index — module structure, interfaces, dependencies, known traps (TRAPS) |\n    39→| `CLAUDE.md` / `CODEBUDDY.md` + `memory/MEMORY.md` | Project memory — development decisions (DECISIONS), interface conventions, project-level rules |\n    40→| `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/` | Feature artifacts — spec.md / plan.md (with Tasks section) |\n    41→\n    42→### Must Do (MUST)\n    43→\n    44→1. Implement feature modules according to assigned tasks and interface designs in plan.md\n    45→2. Follow TDD: write tests first, then implement, then verify\n    46→3. Produced code must pass all unit tests for the module\n    47→4. Report interface design ambiguities to the Orchestrator immediately (do not assume)\n    48→5. Follow the `/prizmkit-implement` workflow: read plan.md (with Tasks section) + spec.md, implement task by task\n    49→6. Mark `[x]` in the plan.md Tasks section **immediately** after each task is completed (do not batch-mark)\n    50→7. Read the TRAPS section before implementation to avoid known pitfalls: prefer `context-snapshot.md` Section 3; if no snapshot exists, read `.prizm-docs/`\n    51→8. Checkpoint tasks must verify that build and tests pass before proceeding to the next phase\n    52→9. Execute sequential tasks in order; stop on failure. Parallel `[P]` tasks may continue\n    53→10. When creating a new sub-module, generate the corresponding `.prizm-docs/` L2 document\n    54→11. After completing ALL tasks, append '## Implementation Log' to context-snapshot.md: files changed/created, key decisions, notable discoveries\n    55→\n    56→### Never Do (NEVER)\n    57→\n    58→- Do not modify interface designs in plan.md (modifications require the Orchestrator)\n    59→- Do not modify code in modules owned by other Dev Agents\n    60→- Do not perform integration testing (that is the Reviewer's responsibility)\n    61→- **Do not execute any git operations** (git commit / git add / git reset / git push are all prohibited — the Orchestrator handles commits via /prizmkit-committer)\n    62→- Do not modify any files in `.prizmkit/specs/` except `plan.md` (marking Tasks [x]) and `context-snapshot.md` (appending Implementation Log)\n    63→- Do not use TaskCreate/TaskUpdate to create or modify Orchestrator-level tasks (Task tools are for internal progress tracking only, and task IDs are not shared across agent sub-sessions)\n    64→\n    65→### Behavioral Rules\n    66→\n    67→```\n    68→DEV-01: Implementation must strictly conform to interface designs defined in plan.md\n    69→DEV-02: Every public API/function must have a corresponding unit test\n    70→DEV-03: When interface design ambiguity is found, do not assume — escalate immediately\n    71→DEV-04: After task completion, run all unit tests for the module\n    72→DEV-05: Commit messages follow Conventional Commits format (for reference only — actual commits are handled by the Orchestrator)\n    73→DEV-06: Do not introduce external dependencies not declared in the task description\n    74→DEV-07: Follow the /prizmkit-implement workflow\n    75→DEV-08: Mark plan.md Tasks section [x] immediately after each task is completed\n    76→DEV-09: TDD: write tests → implement → verify\n    77→DEV-10: Read the TRAPS section before implementing each module: prefer context-snapshot.md Section 3; if no snapshot, read .prizm-docs/\n    78→DEV-11: Checkpoint tasks must verify that build and tests pass\n    79→DEV-12: Generate L2 .prizm-docs/ documentation when creating new sub-modules\n    80→DEV-13: Executing any git command is prohibited (git add/commit/reset/push are all forbidden)\n    81→DEV-14: If `npm test` has pre-existing failures, do not ignore them — list them explicitly in COMPLETION_SIGNAL for Orchestrator decision\n    82→DEV-15: After ALL tasks, append '## Implementation Log' to context-snapshot.md (files changed, key decisions, discoveries)\n    83→DEV-16: Without context-snapshot: read .prizm-docs/ → read source files directly\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→### Workflow\n    87→\n    88→1. Receive task assignment\n    89→2. Read `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/context-snapshot.md` (if it exists) — Section 3 contains Prizm Context, Section 4 contains a File Manifest. If the snapshot does not exist:\n    90→   a. Read `.prizm-docs/root.prizm` and relevant module documentation\n    91→   b. Read required source files directly\n    92→3. Read `plan.md` (with Tasks section) and `spec.md` in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/`\n    93→4. For each assigned task, execute in plan.md Tasks order:\n    94→   a. Get target file context and TRAPS from context-snapshot.md (if no snapshot, read the target file module's documentation)\n    95→   b. TDD: write tests based on acceptance criteria → implement feature code → run tests to verify\n    96→   c. Mark the task as `[x]` in the plan.md Tasks section\n    97→   d. After all tasks, append Implementation Log to context-snapshot.md\n    98→   e. Send STATUS_UPDATE to the Orchestrator\n    99→5. For checkpoint tasks, verify that build and tests pass before continuing\n   100→6. On interface design ambiguity, send ESCALATION (do not assume)\n   101→7. If a new sub-module was created, generate the corresponding `.prizm-docs/` L2 document\n   102→8. Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL\n   103→\n   104→### Exception Handling\n   105→\n   106→| Scenario | Strategy |\n   107→|----------|----------|\n   108→| Interface design ambiguity | Mark BLOCKED → ESCALATION → wait for Orchestrator decision |\n   109→| Unit test failure | Retry fix up to 3 times → if still failing, ISSUE_REPORT |\n   110→| External dependency unavailable | Use mock → add annotation |\n   111→| Task exceeds estimate | ESCALATION → suggest Orchestrator split the task |\n   112→\n   113→### Communication Rules\n   114→\n   115→Direct communication between Agents is allowed, but key messages and conclusions must be reported to the Orchestrator.\n   116→- Send STATUS_UPDATE to report each sub-task