{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01PRK2n9CwWvW4mDHFEecQrt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Context Snapshot — F-020: Enhanced Terminal Output Streaming\n     2→\n     3→## Section 1 — Feature Brief\n     4→\n     5→### Description\n     6→电脑端 AI CLI 的完整终端输出实时映射到手机端，让手机端看到的内容与电脑终端一致。当前 Telegram 的流式输出存在信息丢失（ANSI 颜色码被忽略、进度条显示异常、长输出截断不智能）。\n     7→\n     8→增强内容：\n     9→- ANSI 转义码适配 — 将终端颜色码转换为 Telegram 可展示的格式（如 emoji 状态标记、粗体/斜体替代），或干净地剥离无法展示的控制字符\n    10→- 进度信息适配 — 检测并合并重复的进度行（\\r 覆盖行），避免 Telegram 刷屏\n    11→- 智能分段 — 按逻辑边界（代码块、段落）而非硬性字符数分段\n    12→- 输出历史回溯 — /output [N] 查看最近 N 条命令的完整输出历史\n    13→\n    14→### Acceptance Criteria\n    15→- AC1: AI CLI 输出中的 ANSI 颜色码被正确处理（转换或剥离），不出现乱码\n    16→- AC2: 终端进度条和 \\r 覆盖行被合并为单条进度更新，不刷屏\n    17→- AC3: 长输出按代码块、段落等逻辑边界分段，不在代码中间截断\n    18→- AC4: /output 可查看最近命令的完整输出历史，支持指定条数\n    19→- AC5: 流式输出的延迟不超过 2 秒（从电脑端产生到手机端显示）\n    20→- AC6: 输出格式在手机端阅读体验良好，信息密度适中\n    21→\n    22→---\n    23→\n    24→## Section 2 — Project Structure\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→src/\n    28→├── adapters/          # External adapters\n    29→├── bot/               # Telegram bot\n    30→│   ├── commands/      # Command handlers\n    31→│   │   ├── handlers/  # Individual command handler files\n    32→│   │   ├── index.js\n    33→│   │   ├── help.js\n    34→│   │   └── ...\n    35→│   └── telegram.js    # Main bot setup (~1013 lines)\n    36→├── http/              # HTTP server\n    37→├── pipeline-infra/    # Pipeline infrastructure\n    38→├── routes/            # Express API routes\n    39→│   └── api-routes.js\n    40→├── security/          # Security guards\n    41→├── services/          # Core services\n    42→│   ├── ai-cli-service.js      # AI CLI executor (564 lines)\n    43→│   ├── message-router.js      # F-018 message router (128 lines)\n    44→│   ├── output-pager-service.js # Output pagination (F-009)\n    45→│   ├── realtime-hub.js        # SSE pub/sub (35 lines)\n    46→│   ├── session-store.js       # Session state (427 lines)\n    47→│   └── ...\n    48→├── utils/\n    49→│   ├── logger.js\n    50→│   └── markdown-v2-formatter.js  # Telegram MarkdownV2 utilities\n    51→└── config.js\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→---\n    55→\n    56→## Section 3 — Prizm Context\n    57→\n    58→### root.prizm\n    59→- All HTTP routes use src/routes/api-routes.js as entry point\n    60→- Telegram bot uses Telegraf framework with command handlers in src/bot/commands/\n    61→- Services are registered in src/services/index.js\n    62→- MUST use messageRouter.processMessage() for all chat messages (Web + Telegram) — do not call executeAiCli directly for chat\n    63→- MUST call sessionBind.ensureReady() before any sync method in async route handlers\n    64→\n    65→### services.prizm TRAPS\n    66→- SessionBindingService uses deferred init — always call ensureReady() before sync methods in async contexts\n    67→- messageRouter does not expose heartbeat hooks — Telegram heartbeat progress disabled after F-018 migration\n    68→- Runtime bindings created via POST /api/bind do NOT auto-subscribe realtimeHub for cross-channel push (F-018 gap)\n    69→- config-service originalEnvValues captured at module init; if env vars set after import, use setConfig first\n    70→\n    71→### bot.prizm TRAPS\n    72→- Telegram bot text handler uses messageRouter.processMessage() (F-018) — no longer calls executeAiCli directly\n    73→- Cross-channel push only subscribes for bindings that exist at bot startup; dynamic bindings via API need manual subscribeCrossChannel() call\n    74→- Heartbeat progress messages disabled after F-018 migration to messageRouter (messageRouter lacks onHeartbeat hook)\n    75→- bot._f018 is an internal namespace — not a stable public API\n    76→\n    77→### routes.prizm TRAPS\n    78→- All F-018 endpoints (bind/unbind/bindings/chat/reset) call await sessionBind.ensureReady() — must await before calling sync methods\n    79→- /api/events replays full message history on connect — could be large for long sessions\n    80→\n    81→---\n    82→\n    83→## Section 4 — File Manifest\n    84→\n    85→### Files to Modify\n    86→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n    87→|------|-----------|----------------|\n    88→| `src/bot/telegram.js` | Add /output command, enhance splitMessage with logical segmentation, integrate ANSI/progress adapter | `createEditableStreamPublisher(ctx)`, `splitMessage(text, chunkSize)`, `replyLargeText(ctx, text)`, command handler registration |\n    89→| `src/services/session-store.js` | Store output history per session (per command execution) | `append(key, role, content)`, `setOutputPages(sessionId, pages)`, `getOutputPages(sessionId)` |\n    90→| `src/routes/api-routes.js` | Possibly expose /api/output endpoint | `createApiRouter({realtimeHub, sessionBind, messageRouter, sessionStore})` |\n    91→\n    92→### Files to Create\n    93→| File | Purpose |\n    94→|------|---------|\n    95→| `src/utils/ansi-adapter.js` | ANSI escape code stripping/conversion for Telegram |\n    96→| `src/utils/output-segmenter.js` | Smart segmentation by logical boundaries (code blocks, paragraphs) |\n    97→| `src/services/output-history-service.js` | Per-session command output history storage and retrieval |\n    98→| `src/bot/commands/handlers/output.js` | /output command handler |\n    99→| `tests/utils/ansi-adapter.test.js` | Unit tests for ANSI adapter |\n   100→| `tests/utils/output-segmenter.test.js` | Unit tests for output segmenter |\n   101→| `tests/services/output-history-service.test.js` | Unit tests for output history service |\n   102→| `tests/bot/commands/output.test.js` | Unit tests for /output command |\n   103→\n   104→### Files for Reference\n   105→| File | Why Needed | Key Interfaces |\n   106→|------|-----------|----------------|\n   107→| `src/services/ai-cli-service.js` | Understand onChunk hook and output flow | `executeAiCli(options)`, `hooks.onChunk(text)` — called on each stdout chunk |\n   108→| `src/services/message-router.js` | Understand message routing and hook passing | `processMessage({channel, sessionId, message, hooks})`, `hooks.onAssistantChunk(data)` |\n   109→| `src/services/output-pager-service.js` | Reference for output pagination pattern | `paginateOutput(text, chunkSize)`, `storeOutputPages(sessionId, pages)`, `getNextPage(sessionId)` |\n   110→| `src/utils/markdown-v2-formatter.js` | Telegram formatting utilities | `escapeMarkdownV2(text)`, `convertToMarkdownV2(text)` |\n   111→| `src/bot/commands/handlers/more.js` | Reference for /more command pattern | Shows how to implement pagination commands |\n   112→\n   113→### Known TRAPS\n   114→- `splitMessage()` in telegram.js uses hard character boundary (every 3800 chars) — splits mid-code-block. The fix should use logical boundaries.\n   115→- `onChunk` hook in `executeAiCli` receives raw stdout which may contain ANSI escape codes — these must be stripped before forwarding to Telegram\n   116→- Progress bars use `\\r` (carriage return) to overwrite previous line — accumulating these as normal chunks creates spam. Must detect and coalesce.\n   117→- Telegram message edit API has rate limits — rapid chunk edits can trigger 429 errors. Current flush interval of 1200ms mitigates this.\n   118→- `STREAM_MIN_CHARS = 220` in telegram.js prevents too-frequent edits — keep this threshold when adding smart segmentation.\n   119→- The output history must track FULL output (pre-split) — do not store per-segment chunks.\n   120→\n   121→## Implementation Log\n   122→\n   123→### Files Created\n   124→- `src/utils/ansi-adapter.js` — ANSI escape code stripping and \\r progress line collapsing. Exports: stripAnsi, collapseCarriageReturns, processChunk.\n   125→- `src/utils/output-segmenter.js` — Smart text segmentation at code block / paragraph boundaries. Exports: segmentOutput. Default max 3800 chars.\n   126→- `src/services/output-history-service.js` — In-memory ring buffer factory. Exports: createOutputHistoryService. Default 10 entries per session.\n   127→- `src/bot/commands/handlers/output.js` — /output [N] command handler. Exports: outputMeta, handleOutput, outputHistoryService (singleton).\n   128→- `tests/utils/ansi-adapter.test.js` — 24 unit tests (all pass)\n   129→- `tests/utils/output-segmenter.test.js` — 13 unit tests (all pass)\n   130→- `tests/services/output-history-service.test.js` — 16 unit tests (all pass)\n   131→- `tests/bot/commands/handlers/output.test.js` — 12 unit tests (all pass)\n   132→- `.prizm-docs/src/utils/ansi-adapter.prizm` — L2 doc\n   133→- `.prizm-docs/src/utils/output-segmenter.prizm` — L2 doc\n   134→- `.prizm-docs/src/services/output-history-service.prizm` — L2 doc\n   135→\n   136→### Files Modified\n   137→- `src/bot/telegram.js` — 4 integration changes:\n   138→  1. Added imports: outputMeta, handleOutput, outputHistoryService, ansiProcessChunk, segmentOutput\n   139→  2. Registered /output command in registerPipelineCommands()\n   140→  3. In onAssistantChunk hook: wraps chunk with ansiProcessChunk() before pushing to streamPublisher\n   141→  4. In render() inside createEditableStreamPublisher: replaced splitMessage() with segmentOutput()\n   142→  5. After streamPublisher.finish(): calls outputHistoryService.addOutput(sessionKey, userMessage, replyText)\n   143→- `.prizm-docs/src/utils.prizm` — Added ansi-adapter.js and output-segmenter.js to FILES and INTERFACES\n   144→- `.prizm-docs/src/services.prizm` — Added output-history-service.js to FILES and INTERFACES\n   145→\n   146→### Key Implementation Decisions\n   147→\n   148→1. TDD order: Tests were written before implementation for each module pair (T1/T2, T3/T4, T5/T6, T7/T8). All tests drove the implementations.\n   149→\n   150→2. ANSI regex coverage: The ANSI_REGEX covers OSC sequences (ESC ] ... BEL), CSI sequences (ESC [ ... final byte), and simple two-char ESC sequences. This handles all common ANSI escape codes including 256-color and RGB color codes.\n   151→\n   152→3. carriage return collapsing strategy: Split on \\n first to preserve newlines, then collapse \\r segments within each logical line by keeping only the last segment. This correctly handles both \\r and \\r\\n mixed input.\n   153→\n   154→4. Code block detection in segmenter: Count ``` fences — odd count means inside an open code block. When a split point would fall inside a code block, back up to find the last code block start and try to split before it.\n   155→\n   156→5. outputHistoryService singleton pattern: The singleton is created in output.js and exported for re-use by telegram.js. Tests inject a mock via handlerCtx.outputHistoryService — this avoids polluting the shared singleton during tests.\n   157→\n   158→6. Session key format for output history: telegram.js stores under `telegram:{sessionId}` (matching the message router's session key format). The /output handler prefixes `telegram:` if the sessionId doesn't already have it, ensuring the lookup always hits the correct key.\n   159→\n   160→7. Output history records FULL pre-split output: The raw routerResult.reply is stored (before file marker extraction or segmentation), per the TRAP noted in context-snapshot.md. This preserves the complete output for later retrieval.\n   161→\n   162→8. subscribeCrossChannel still uses splitMessage(): The cross-channel push path was intentionally NOT changed to use segmentOutput() — it is separate from the streaming path and out of scope for F-020.\n   163→\n   164→### Pre-existing Test Failures (not caused by F-020)\n   165→The following 38 test failures existed before F-020 implementation (confirmed by git diff showing none of these test files were modified):\n   166→- tests/integration/f002-command-router.integration.test.js — 5 failures: mock ctx missing .chat property\n   167→- tests/integration/ai-cli-markdownv2.test.js — 1 failure: nested code in bold\n   168→- tests/integration/commit*.test.js — ~10 failures: non-admin amend/force timeouts\n   169→- tests/pipeline-infra/path-policy-python-compat.test.js — 5 failures: Python path_policy module missing\n   170→- tests/integration/ — various: typecheck, lint, static checks\n   171→- tests/services/status-aggregator.test.js — 1 failure: formatStatusForTelegram\n   172→- tests/services/telegram-pusher.test.js — 1 failure: sendFile document\n   173→- tests/bot/commands/handlers/logs.test.js — 2 failures\n   174→- tests/bot/commands/handlers/tail.test.js — 2 failures\n   175→- tests/services/command-executor-service.test.js — 1 failure\n   176→- tests/bot/commands/web-command-router.test.js — 1 failure (F-015 NL routing)\n   177→- tests/security/permission-guard.test.js — 4 failures\n   178→\n   179→### Notable Discoveries\n   180→- The `render()` function inside `createEditableStreamPublisher` is a closure — the segmentOutput() replacement is a single-line change at line ~408 of telegram.js.\n   181→- The `STREAM_MIN_CHARS` threshold (220) is preserved — the segmentOutput() only changes HOW segments are cut, not WHEN renders happen. The streaming frequency is unchanged.\n   182→- The /output command uses handlerCtx.outputHistoryService injection for testability without needing to mock module-level imports.\n   183→\n   184→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_018ui2JaLFAdK8jTBEzEzMKD","session_id":"ac44fc5c-0407-4bd5-95fd-57d4b24826fc","uuid":"86d72ac6-c180-4ffd-8782-08fd6849881c","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:52:02.515Z"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01RmfTeXL83v67J24uEgDPUg","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: prizm-dev-team-reviewer\n     3→description: PrizmKit-integrated quality reviewer. Uses /prizmkit-analyze for cross-document consistency, /prizmkit-code-review for spec compliance and code quality, and writes integration tests. Use when performing analysis, testing, or code review.\n     4→tools:\n     5→  - Read\n     6→  - Write\n     7→  - Edit\n     8→  - Bash\n     9→  - Glob\n    10→  - Grep\n    11→  - Task\n    12→  - SendMessage\n    13→model: inherit\n    14→skills: prizmkit-code-review, prizmkit-analyze, prizmkit-prizm-docs\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→You are the **Reviewer Agent**, the quality reviewer of the PrizmKit-integrated Multi-Agent software development collaboration team.\n    18→\n    19→### Core Identity\n    20→\n    21→You are the team's \"quality inspector + proofreader\" — you do not produce the product but ensure its quality. You are responsible for two phases:\n    22→1. **Cross-validation (Phase 4)**: Before implementation, use `/prizmkit-analyze` to check consistency across spec/plan/tasks\n    23→2. **Review (Phase 6)**: After implementation, use `/prizmkit-code-review` to check code quality, and write and execute integration tests\n    24→\n    25→### Project Context\n    26→\n    27→Project documentation is in `.prizm-docs/`. Before review, read `context-snapshot.md` (if it exists in `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/`); its Section 3 contains Prizm Context (RULES, PATTERNS, TRAPS). Section 4 contains a File Manifest. The '## Implementation Log' section (if present) describes what Dev changed and key decisions. If the snapshot does not exist, read `root.prizm` to understand project rules.\n    28→\n    29→### Artifact Paths\n    30→\n    31→| Path | Purpose |\n    32→|------|---------|\n    33→| `.prizm-docs/` | Architecture index — module structure, interfaces, dependencies, known traps (TRAPS) |\n    34→| `CLAUDE.md` / `CODEBUDDY.md` + `memory/MEMORY.md` | Project memory — development decisions (DECISIONS), interface conventions, project-level rules |\n    35→| `.prizmkit/specs/###-feature-name/` | Feature artifacts — spec.md / plan.md (with Tasks section) |\n    36→\n    37→### Must Do (MUST)\n    38→\n    39→1. In Phase 4, run `/prizmkit-analyze` for cross-consistency validation\n    40→2. In Phase 6, run `/prizmkit-code-review` for spec compliance and code quality review\n    41→3. In Phase 6, write and execute integration tests to verify cross-module interactions\n    42→4. Verify that actual implementation conforms to interface designs in plan.md\n    43→5. Verify the integrity and correctness of cross-module data flows\n    44→6. Test boundary conditions and exception paths\n    45→7. Check that code conforms to `.prizm-docs/` RULES and PATTERNS\n    46→8. Review is a **read-only operation** (the review portions of Phase 4 and Phase 6 do not modify code files)\n    47→9. Integration test cases must cover all user stories defined in spec.md\n    48→10. After completing review, append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md: issues found (severity), test results, final verdict\n    49→11. During review, read the '## Implementation Log' section of context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's changes and decisions\n    50→\n    51→### Never Do (NEVER)\n    52→\n    53→- Do not write implementation code (that is Dev's responsibility)\n    54→- Do not decompose tasks (that is the Orchestrator's responsibility)\n    55→- Do not perform task scheduling (that is the Orchestrator's responsibility)\n    56→- **Do not execute any git operations** (git commit / git add / git reset / git push are all prohibited)\n    57→- Do not use TaskCreate/TaskUpdate to create or modify Orchestrator-level tasks (Task tools are for internal progress tracking only, and task IDs are not shared across agent sub-sessions)\n    58→\n    59→### Behavioral Rules\n    60→\n    61→```\n    62→REV-01: In Phase 4, use /prizmkit-analyze for cross-validation\n    63→REV-02: In Phase 6, use /prizmkit-code-review for code review\n    64→REV-03: Every finding must reference a specific file path and line number\n    65→REV-04: CRITICAL-level findings must include a specific fix recommendation\n    66→REV-05: Maximum 30 findings (maintain actionability)\n    67→REV-06: Spec compliance failures are always HIGH or CRITICAL\n    68→REV-07: Security findings are always HIGH or CRITICAL\n    69→REV-08: Integration tests must cover all user stories in spec.md\n    70→REV-09: Review code for conformance to .prizm-docs/ PATTERNS and RULES\n    71→REV-10: Do not use the timeout command (incompatible with macOS). Run tests directly with node --test or npm test without a timeout prefix\n    72→REV-11: After review, append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md (issues, severity, test results, verdict)\n    73→REV-12: Read Implementation Log in context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's decisions; reference relevant decisions in the review report\n    74→```\n    75→\n    76→### Phase 4 Workflow: Cross-Validation\n    77→\n    78→**Precondition**: Orchestrator has completed spec.md / plan.md (with Tasks section)\n    79→\n    80→1. Invoke the `/prizmkit-analyze` skill (**not a CLI command** — invoke via the Skill tool or the `/prizmkit-analyze` directive)\n    81→   - Input: spec.md, plan.md (with Tasks section)\n    82→   - 6 detection channels: duplication detection, ambiguity detection, incompleteness detection, Prizm rule alignment, coverage gaps, inconsistencies\n    83→   - Output: consistency analysis report (conversation output only)\n    84→   - If the Skill tool is unavailable, manually perform cross-consistency analysis following the 6 detection channels\n    85→2. If CRITICAL issues are found, report to the Orchestrator for rollback and fix\n    86→3. Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with analysis results)\n    87→\n    88→### Phase 6 Workflow: Review\n    89→\n    90→**Precondition**: Dev has completed implementation; all tasks are marked `[x]`\n    91→\n    92→1. Read `context-snapshot.md` (if it exists); its Section 3 contains RULES and PATTERNS. If the snapshot does not exist, read `.prizm-docs/root.prizm`\n    93→2. Read '## Implementation Log' in context-snapshot.md to understand Dev's changes and decisions\n    94→3. Run `/prizmkit-code-review` (read-only)\n    95→   - 6 review dimensions: spec compliance, plan adherence, code quality, security, consistency, test coverage\n    96→   - Verdict: PASS | PASS WITH WARNINGS | NEEDS FIXES\n    97→3. Write and execute integration tests:\n    98→   - Interface compliance (request format, response format)\n    99→   - Cross-module data flow integrity\n   100→   - User story acceptance criteria (from spec.md)\n   101→   - Boundary conditions and exception paths\n   102→4. Generate a unified review report\n   103→5. Append '## Review Notes' to context-snapshot.md (issues found, severity, test results, verdict)\n   104→6. Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with verdict)\n   105→\n   106→### Verdict Criteria\n   107→\n   108→| Verdict | Condition | Follow-up Action |\n   109→|---------|-----------|-----------------|\n   110→| **PASS** | No CRITICAL or HIGH findings | Proceed to the next phase |\n   111→| **PASS_WITH_WARNINGS** | No CRITICAL, but HIGH findings exist | Record items for improvement; may proceed to the next phase |\n   112→| **NEEDS_FIXES** | CRITICAL findings exist | Return to Dev for fixes, then re-review |\n   113→\n   114→### Severity Levels\n   115→\n   116→| Level | Definition | Examples |\n   117→|-------|-----------|----------|\n   118→| CRITICAL | Security risk or severe architectural issue | SQL injection, hardcoded secrets |\n   119→| HIGH | Significant issue affecting maintainability | Spec non-compliance, excessive code duplication |\n   120→| MEDIUM | Code quality improvement | Inconsistent naming, missing comments |\n   121→| LOW | Style suggestion | Minor formatting, optional optimization |\n   122→\n   123→### Exception Handling\n   124→\n   125→| Scenario | Strategy |\n   126→|----------|----------|\n   127→| Analyze finds CRITICAL | Report to Orchestrator → rollback for fix |\n   128→| Code-review finds CRITICAL | Report to Orchestrator → return to Dev for fix |\n   129→| Integration test failure | Classify severity → ISSUE_REPORT → Orchestrator assigns to Dev |\n   130→| Findings exceed 30 | Keep only the 30 most severe |\n   131→| Prizm RULES violation | Automatically classify as CRITICAL |\n   132→\n   133→### Communication Rules\n   134→\n   135→Direct communication between Agents is allowed, but key messages and conclusions must be reported to the Orchestrator.\n   136→- Send COMPLETION_SIGNAL (with verdict) to indicate completion\n   137→- Send ISSUE_REPORT to report CRITICAL findings\n   138→- Receive TASK_ASSIGNMENT to get assigned work\n   139→\n   140→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_018ui2JaLFAdK8jTBEzEzMKD","session_id":"ac44fc5c-0407-4bd5-95fd-57d4b24826fc","uuid":"16d83102-b2de-4381-8023-5c8663bd0d9d","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:52:02.517Z"}
