utils/ansi-adapter\nFILES: ansi-adapter.js\nRESPONSIBILITY: Strip ANSI escape codes and collapse carriage-return progress lines for Telegram display\nKEY_FILES:\n- ansi-adapter.js: 3 exported functions, ~100 lines. Pure string transformation, no I/O.\nDEPENDENCIES:\n- uses: none (no external dependencies)\n- imported-by: src/bot/telegram.js (onAssistantChunk hook)\nTRAPS:\n- ANSI_REGEX must cover OSC sequences (ESC ] ... BEL), CSI sequences (ESC [ ... final), and simple two-char sequences — incomplete regex misses hyperlinks and window-title codes\n- collapseCarriageReturns splits on \\n first, then collapses \\r within each line — do NOT split on \\r globally or \\r\\n lines will be mangled\n- processChunk applies stripAnsi THEN collapseCarriageReturns — order matters; reversing creates garbled output on ANSI-colored progress bars\n- Returns '' for null/undefined inputs — callers should not rely on passthrough of falsy values\nCHANGELOG:\n- 2026-03-22 | add: initial module for F-020 ANSI stripping and progress-line collapsing\nUPDATED: 2026-03-22\n","numLines":17,"startLine":1,"totalLines":17}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01ARjkZdsnSYmQQKhmticUYX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→MODULE: src/services/output-history-service\n     2→FILES: output-history-service.js\n     3→RESPONSIBILITY: In-memory ring buffer storing per-session AI CLI command output history for /output command retrieval\n     4→KEY_FILES:\n     5→- output-history-service.js: factory function, ~80 lines. No I/O, no external deps.\n     6→DEPENDENCIES:\n     7→- uses: none (no external dependencies)\n     8→- imported-by: src/bot/commands/handlers/output.js (singleton instance)\n     9→- imported-by: src/bot/telegram.js (via output.js re-export)\n    10→TRAPS:\n    11→- Ring buffer implemented with Array.push() + Array.shift() — not a true circular buffer. Performance is O(n) for eviction; acceptable for maxEntries <= 10.\n    12→- outputHistoryService singleton is created inside output.js — telegram.js imports and uses this singleton. Tests must inject a mock via handlerCtx.outputHistoryService or they will mutate the shared singleton.\n    13→- Session key format is telegram:{chatId} — must match the key used in telegram.js addOutput() call. If session key format changes in F-018, this must be updated.\n    14→- getHistory() returns a slice of the internal array — returned objects are the same references. Callers must not mutate entries.\n    15→- getHistory(sessionKey, 0) returns [] — count=0 is treated as \"no entries requested\".\n    16→CHANGELOG:\n    17→- 2026-03-22 | add: initial module for F-020 output history ring buffer\n    18→UPDATED: 2026-03-22\n    19→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac44fc5c-0407-4bd5-95fd-57d4b24826fc","uuid":"cde8cb88-d0c5-406f-aa92-2c8d19199acd","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:57:55.950Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/loneyu/SelfProjects/PrizmClaw/.prizm-docs/src/services/output-history-service.prizm","content":"MODULE: src/services/output-history-service\nFILES: output-history-service.js\nRESPONSIBILITY: In-memory ring buffer storing per-session AI CLI command output history for /output command retrieval\nKEY_FILES:\n- output-history-service.js: factory function, ~80 lines. No I/O, no external deps.\nDEPENDENCIES:\n- uses: none (no external dependencies)\n- imported-by: src/bot/commands/handlers/output.js (singleton instance)\n- imported-by: src/bot/telegram.js (via output.js re-export)\nTRAPS:\n- Ring buffer implemented with Array.push() + Array.shift() — not a true circular buffer. Performance is O(n) for eviction; acceptable for maxEntries <= 10.\n- outputHistoryService singleton is created inside output.js — telegram.js imports and uses this singleton. Tests must inject a mock via handlerCtx.outputHistoryService or they will mutate the shared singleton.\n- Session key format is telegram:{chatId} — must match the key used in telegram.js addOutput() call. If session key format changes in F-018, this must be updated.\n- getHistory() returns a slice of the internal array — returned objects are the same references. Callers must not mutate entries.\n- getHistory(sessionKey, 0) returns [] — count=0 is treated as \"no entries requested\".\nCHANGELOG:\n- 2026-03-22 | add: initial module for F-020 output history ring buffer\nUPDATED: 2026-03-22\n","numLines":19,"startLine":1,"totalLines":19}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01F3HVSnvJ7vbeY1HL35Mr4Z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→MODULE: src/utils/output-segmenter\n     2→FILES: output-segmenter.js\n     3→RESPONSIBILITY: Smart text segmentation at logical boundaries (code blocks, paragraphs) for Telegram messages\n     4→KEY_FILES:\n     5→- output-segmenter.js: 1 exported function + 4 private helpers, ~130 lines. Pure string transformation.\n     6→DEPENDENCIES:\n     7→- uses: none (no external dependencies)\n     8→- imported-by: src/bot/telegram.js (createEditableStreamPublisher render() function)\n     9→TRAPS:\n    10→- Code block detection counts ``` occurrences — odd count means inside a block. This counts inline triple-backticks too; strings with malformed fences will misdetect.\n    11→- Splits at paragraph (\\n\\n) first, then newline (\\n), then space — never hard-cuts at arbitrary byte boundary unless forced (no logical boundary found).\n    12→- Default maxChunkSize is 3800, NOT 4096 — Telegram limit is 4096 but 3800 gives safety margin for metadata overhead.\n    13→- findCodeBlockEnd searches for closing ``` AFTER the opening fence — if closing fence is missing (incomplete stream), it returns maxChunkSize as fallback (hard cut).\n    14→- Replaces splitMessage() in the render() function inside createEditableStreamPublisher — NOT in the cross-channel push path (subscribeCrossChannel still uses splitMessage).\n    15→CHANGELOG:\n    16→- 2026-03-22 | add: initial module for F-020 smart output segmentation\n    17→UPDATED: 2026-03-22\n    18→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ac44fc5c-0407